WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.140
 Now I wanna talk a little bit about how you or us,

00:00:04.140 --> 00:00:06.520
 we can create our own tags

00:00:06.520 --> 00:00:08.960
 and then use them throughout our markup.

00:00:08.960 --> 00:00:13.000
 So what is this whole thing about creating new tags?

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:15.600
 Well, programmers hate to repeat themselves.

00:00:15.600 --> 00:00:17.960
 It's just from the third week

00:00:17.960 --> 00:00:19.360
 of learning how to write software,

00:00:19.360 --> 00:00:23.000
 it's all about don't repeat yourself, D-R-Y.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:26.680
 And that's because if you write the same code over and over,

00:00:26.680 --> 00:00:29.220
 especially if there are tiny changes in that code

00:00:29.220 --> 00:00:32.820
 or little like if then else's, it really causes errors.

00:00:32.820 --> 00:00:34.520
 And if you have a bunch of code,

00:00:34.520 --> 00:00:36.920
 and by now you've seen this in this course,

00:00:36.920 --> 00:00:40.140
 if you cut and paste and make small changes

00:00:40.140 --> 00:00:41.800
 and then paste and make small changes

00:00:41.800 --> 00:00:46.120
 and paste and make small changes, it's convenient.

00:00:46.120 --> 00:00:48.420
 You're repeating yourself and then making changes.

00:00:48.420 --> 00:00:49.720
 But what if you started with a bug

00:00:49.720 --> 00:00:50.880
 and all that stuff, you paste it,

00:00:50.880 --> 00:00:54.140
 or you find a bug later and now you got 40 places

00:00:54.140 --> 00:00:55.740
 and you gotta make the same tiny change.

00:00:55.740 --> 00:00:57.520
 It's really frustrating.

00:00:57.520 --> 00:01:01.240
 And this just means that a big part of software

00:01:01.240 --> 00:01:03.560
 is how to avoid repeating ourselves.

00:01:03.560 --> 00:01:07.300
 Things like functions with parameters,

00:01:07.300 --> 00:01:09.780
 object-oriented approaches with base classes

00:01:09.780 --> 00:01:13.080
 that we're extending, the class-based views in Django

00:01:13.080 --> 00:01:14.480
 versus just function views.

00:01:14.480 --> 00:01:16.720
 I mean, the function views are simpler

00:01:16.720 --> 00:01:17.640
 and easier to understand.

00:01:17.640 --> 00:01:20.440
 Class-based views are beautiful and elegant,

00:01:20.440 --> 00:01:22.200
 but hard to understand.

00:01:22.200 --> 00:01:26.160
 Like templates, like the navigation that you've been building.

00:01:26.160 --> 00:01:28.600
 It would say extends baseboostrap.html.

00:01:28.600 --> 00:01:33.600
 That's a way to not put the same navigation tech HTML

00:01:33.600 --> 00:01:34.720
 on every page.

00:01:34.720 --> 00:01:39.040
 And like the percent URL, you can change the remap URLs

00:01:39.040 --> 00:01:42.160
 and urls.py and not have to make changes in your templates.

00:01:42.160 --> 00:01:45.380
 Again, we don't like to repeat ourselves.

00:01:45.380 --> 00:01:49.240
 So what we've been doing up to this point

00:01:49.240 --> 00:01:53.720
 is we've been doing all of our templating in the server.

00:01:53.720 --> 00:01:56.720
 And so if you go way, way back to when we were just looking

00:01:56.720 --> 00:01:58.160
 at views for the first time,

00:01:58.160 --> 00:02:00.420
 this is a function-based view here,

00:02:00.420 --> 00:02:02.200
 but you see this render.

00:02:02.200 --> 00:02:04.160
 Now, if you recall what render does

00:02:04.160 --> 00:02:07.220
 is it takes a template plus a context.

00:02:07.220 --> 00:02:11.080
 In this case, it's a dictionary that's mapping zap to 42

00:02:11.080 --> 00:02:15.640
 and says, render this, give me back some HTML,

00:02:15.640 --> 00:02:17.120
 and then we send it back to the browser.

00:02:17.120 --> 00:02:18.800
 And if you look at the template,

00:02:18.800 --> 00:02:20.560
 you see we've got these little curly braces,

00:02:20.560 --> 00:02:23.120
 double curly braces that says zap says,

00:02:23.120 --> 00:02:26.000
 go into the template and grab the zap value

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:27.400
 and put it in here.

00:02:27.400 --> 00:02:30.280
 And so this is just kind of our model view controller.

00:02:30.280 --> 00:02:31.920
 And this is the big picture.

00:02:31.920 --> 00:02:34.380
 I promised you wouldn't see it very often

00:02:34.380 --> 00:02:37.600
 after the middle of the class, but here it is again.

00:02:37.600 --> 00:02:39.480
 And we take these templates,

00:02:39.480 --> 00:02:42.360
 we pull data into the templates from the models,

00:02:42.360 --> 00:02:45.380
 we make context and we send that back to the browser,

00:02:45.380 --> 00:02:50.180
 classic request response cycle model view controller.

00:02:50.180 --> 00:02:51.760
 So what we're gonna do now

00:02:51.760 --> 00:02:54.060
 is we're gonna take a little tiny bit

00:02:54.060 --> 00:02:57.880
 of that template processing and move it into the browser.

00:02:57.880 --> 00:03:00.780
 We're still gonna have a server-based template,

00:03:00.780 --> 00:03:05.120
 but we're also gonna have a little tiny template

00:03:05.120 --> 00:03:07.040
 in the browser.

00:03:07.040 --> 00:03:09.240
 Let's take a look at how we would do this.

00:03:09.240 --> 00:03:13.720
 And we're doing this by creating our own tag.

00:03:13.720 --> 00:03:15.980
 And so we have a tag.

00:03:15.980 --> 00:03:19.800
 See, it says less than DJ4E dash greeting greater than,

00:03:19.800 --> 00:03:21.160
 that's a tag.

00:03:21.160 --> 00:03:24.000
 It's a tag we invented.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:27.000
 And so we can pass some parameters attributes.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:29.320
 We get to define what those attributes do.

00:03:29.320 --> 00:03:31.320
 We can have a tag that has an ID on it

00:03:31.320 --> 00:03:32.840
 so we can mess with it.

00:03:32.840 --> 00:03:34.960
 I put up a button that says click me.

00:03:34.960 --> 00:03:38.760
 And that script type equals module source equals

00:03:38.760 --> 00:03:41.960
 dot slash 16 DJ4E greet dot JS.

00:03:41.960 --> 00:03:46.960
 That's the code that adds the DJ4E greeting tag

00:03:46.960 --> 00:03:48.020
 to the browser.

00:03:48.020 --> 00:03:53.020
 So once that's imported, it goes and creates the tag

00:03:53.020 --> 00:03:54.880
 and then we can use the tag.

00:03:54.880 --> 00:03:58.400
 And then the little script is simply

00:03:58.400 --> 00:04:00.240
 changing the name attribute.

00:04:00.240 --> 00:04:02.280
 And so we're passing almost as a parameter.

00:04:02.280 --> 00:04:04.760
 Think of it like a function or a macro.

00:04:04.760 --> 00:04:06.320
 It's like a HTML template,

00:04:06.320 --> 00:04:08.020
 which we're about to see in a moment.

00:04:08.020 --> 00:04:10.280
 So name is the thing we're passing in.

00:04:10.280 --> 00:04:12.460
 And not only are we passing it in,

00:04:12.460 --> 00:04:17.060
 but we can change it dynamically based on a DOM event.

00:04:17.060 --> 00:04:19.000
 And that's what the do change is doing.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:23.080
 So let's take a look at what this template is.

00:04:23.080 --> 00:04:26.560
 And so the concept of a custom element,

00:04:26.560 --> 00:04:28.360
 that's something that's been in browsers

00:04:28.360 --> 00:04:30.080
 for quite some time.

00:04:30.080 --> 00:04:32.880
 And if you just write your own custom element,

00:04:32.880 --> 00:04:34.780
 you can do everything we're doing here,

00:04:34.780 --> 00:04:38.400
 but it's a lot more verbose.

00:04:38.400 --> 00:04:42.080
 And so what we do is using object orientation,

00:04:42.080 --> 00:04:45.680
 we're grabbing a little tiny library called LitElement.

00:04:45.680 --> 00:04:48.280
 So LitElement is a custom element

00:04:48.280 --> 00:04:50.720
 that has a lot of base capabilities into it.

00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:53.520
 And so we're extending LitElement

00:04:53.520 --> 00:04:56.120
 to make a class called simple greeting.

00:04:56.120 --> 00:04:58.840
 And that just means there's a lot of boilerplate

00:04:58.840 --> 00:05:01.000
 that we don't have to repeat.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:04.520
 So in it, we tell it our interaction with the outside world.

00:05:04.520 --> 00:05:06.520
 And we say there is a property called name,

00:05:06.520 --> 00:05:08.520
 which turns into an attribute on the tag.

00:05:08.520 --> 00:05:10.640
 If you look back at the tag,

00:05:10.640 --> 00:05:13.200
 we have a constructor and we in that constructor,

00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:15.760
 we call our parent super,

00:05:15.760 --> 00:05:18.040
 that's the constructor of LitElement.

00:05:18.040 --> 00:05:20.680
 And then we set our default value.

00:05:20.680 --> 00:05:22.360
 So it's named somebody.

00:05:22.360 --> 00:05:25.080
 And there's this whole thing,

00:05:25.080 --> 00:05:27.040
 I won't go into it in great detail.

00:05:27.040 --> 00:05:29.720
 There's a thing called a shadow DOM,

00:05:29.720 --> 00:05:34.720
 where you can inherit the CSS and other styling

00:05:34.720 --> 00:05:39.100
 from the enclosing document,

00:05:39.100 --> 00:05:43.360
 or you can have your own CSS inside the LitElement.

00:05:43.360 --> 00:05:47.160
 I'm choosing not to isolate my markup

00:05:47.160 --> 00:05:51.280
 from the enclosing document.

00:05:51.280 --> 00:05:54.000
 And so I'm doing this create render root that says,

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.000
 just put my macro,

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:58.800
 put my text into the enclosing document.

00:05:58.800 --> 00:06:02.640
 And whatever HTML, whatever CSS,

00:06:02.640 --> 00:06:04.440
 JavaScript libraries, et cetera,

00:06:04.440 --> 00:06:06.880
 they're just inherited into my code.

00:06:06.880 --> 00:06:09.960
 You can make these web components in a way

00:06:09.960 --> 00:06:12.000
 that they can go into any HTML

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:14.620
 and they bring their styling with them.

00:06:14.620 --> 00:06:18.200
 I tend to use these where I'm gonna build an application.

00:06:18.200 --> 00:06:20.360
 I want my styling, I want my font,

00:06:20.360 --> 00:06:24.200
 and I want my colors and my spacing and whatever.

00:06:24.200 --> 00:06:26.960
 I want that to be like bootstrap across the whole thing,

00:06:26.960 --> 00:06:29.440
 which is kind of how we're doing it in this class.

00:06:29.440 --> 00:06:31.800
 And so I don't like shadow DOM,

00:06:31.800 --> 00:06:35.280
 but that's another approach

00:06:35.280 --> 00:06:36.960
 is to make these templates

00:06:36.960 --> 00:06:41.840
 super isolated using shadow DOM.

00:06:41.840 --> 00:06:44.440
 But the meat of all this is the render.

00:06:44.440 --> 00:06:47.400
 And again, let's go back and think about the render

00:06:47.400 --> 00:06:49.880
 in the view that I just showed you.

00:06:49.880 --> 00:06:51.360
 What is the render to?

00:06:51.360 --> 00:06:55.800
 It takes some templated HTML and it makes replacements.

00:06:55.800 --> 00:06:59.720
 And you'll notice that this one has curly braces.

00:06:59.720 --> 00:07:01.000
 $this.name.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:04.880
 Well, this is the JavaScript object instance variable

00:07:04.880 --> 00:07:08.080
 and .name is an object attribute.

00:07:08.080 --> 00:07:09.200
 Let's go back.

00:07:09.200 --> 00:07:10.240
 That's name equals.

00:07:10.240 --> 00:07:12.600
 The attribute name equals world, name equals first,

00:07:12.600 --> 00:07:15.520
 and then later I set that to be second.

00:07:15.520 --> 00:07:17.840
 And the return HTML back quote,

00:07:17.840 --> 00:07:19.000
 the back quote's very important.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:20.160
 It's not a forward quote.

00:07:20.160 --> 00:07:23.640
 It's a dynamically rendered template.

00:07:23.640 --> 00:07:27.380
 And what's cool about this is it's responsive,

00:07:27.380 --> 00:07:30.400
 which means that if you change the name attribute

00:07:30.400 --> 00:07:32.720
 on this DJ4E greeting tag,

00:07:32.720 --> 00:07:36.520
 that text in the browser will re-render with the new stuff.

00:07:36.520 --> 00:07:40.360
 And so that's what's happening when you say click me

00:07:40.360 --> 00:07:43.880
 and it turns from hello first to hello second.

00:07:43.880 --> 00:07:46.320
 And so this is, we're not gonna have you write

00:07:46.320 --> 00:07:47.160
 too many of these.

00:07:47.160 --> 00:07:48.400
 I'm gonna give them to you.

00:07:48.400 --> 00:07:52.400
 I'm just showing you how this sort of works.

00:07:52.400 --> 00:07:54.160
 Now, this may seem familiar

00:07:54.160 --> 00:07:56.520
 and you may have taken other classes

00:07:56.520 --> 00:07:58.720
 or you may have learned about things like React

00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:03.720
 or Vue or Svelte or even Java server faces

00:08:03.720 --> 00:08:07.800
 or JSP template tags or spring time leaf.

00:08:07.800 --> 00:08:11.160
 There's all kinds of what I'll call

00:08:11.160 --> 00:08:13.040
 custom component ecosystems.

00:08:13.040 --> 00:08:17.560
 Ways that you can have a tag that you invent, right?

00:08:17.560 --> 00:08:20.500
 Like in React, you can make a function called my button

00:08:20.500 --> 00:08:24.400
 and then you have a new thing called my button

00:08:24.400 --> 00:08:26.280
 and then you can use the my button tag, right?

00:08:26.280 --> 00:08:30.360
 And so there's many ways

00:08:30.360 --> 00:08:32.080
 and I'm not going to tell you

00:08:32.080 --> 00:08:33.960
 not to use React or Vue or Svelte.

00:08:33.960 --> 00:08:36.160
 I like lit and I'm including lit here

00:08:36.160 --> 00:08:37.880
 'cause it's kind of the simplest.

00:08:37.880 --> 00:08:41.100
 It's really almost a foundational capability

00:08:41.100 --> 00:08:44.680
 rather than a fancy custom component ecosystem.

00:08:44.680 --> 00:08:48.040
 And going forward, this seems to me

00:08:48.040 --> 00:08:50.080
 to be just a cool part of the browser

00:08:50.080 --> 00:08:52.780
 and we can use it however we want.

00:08:52.780 --> 00:08:57.440
 And if you look at the trend and the templating,

00:08:57.440 --> 00:08:59.640
 not just the little bits of the template,

00:08:59.640 --> 00:09:01.640
 but eventually whole templates

00:09:01.640 --> 00:09:04.120
 and then much of the Vue,

00:09:04.120 --> 00:09:08.700
 much of the controller moves into the browser.

00:09:08.700 --> 00:09:10.680
 And in the most extreme,

00:09:10.680 --> 00:09:13.140
 the controller and Vue end up completely in the browser.

00:09:13.140 --> 00:09:15.840
 The model is partially in the browser

00:09:15.840 --> 00:09:17.760
 and partially in the server.

00:09:17.760 --> 00:09:21.080
 And then we have JSON and web services

00:09:21.080 --> 00:09:24.040
 so that the actual persistent and permanent data

00:09:24.040 --> 00:09:26.160
 is still stored in the server.

00:09:26.160 --> 00:09:29.360
 But pretty much all the markup is in the browser

00:09:29.360 --> 00:09:32.800
 and that makes it so that it can be very, very responsive.

00:09:32.800 --> 00:09:36.740
 And ironically, JSON is the next topic in this class.

00:09:36.740 --> 00:09:40.000
 So we're first learning about how to make these tags

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:41.820
 and then we'll learn how to feed data

00:09:41.820 --> 00:09:44.040
 from the server in these tags.

00:09:44.040 --> 00:09:49.040
 And so a kind of a very modern futuristic application

00:09:49.640 --> 00:09:52.620
 will tend to have the model view in the controller

00:09:52.620 --> 00:09:54.680
 often running mostly in JavaScript.

00:09:54.680 --> 00:09:57.240
 You need a little bit from the server to get it started.

00:09:57.240 --> 00:09:59.800
 But then you have this thing called REST web services

00:09:59.800 --> 00:10:03.800
 and the views will read and write data in the database

00:10:03.800 --> 00:10:06.080
 using REST web services.

00:10:06.080 --> 00:10:09.840
 And so that's kind of what we're going to go do next.

00:10:09.840 --> 00:10:13.200
 And that is how to talk and exchange data

00:10:13.200 --> 00:10:16.680
 from the browser in JavaScript and the server.

00:10:16.680 --> 00:10:19.920
 So in this section, we talked about JavaScript

00:10:19.920 --> 00:10:22.300
 and the browser, document object model,

00:10:22.300 --> 00:10:25.380
 what is the window, adding handlers,

00:10:25.380 --> 00:10:28.600
 adding DOM event handlers, window event handlers,

00:10:28.600 --> 00:10:32.560
 how we can grab and change data in the document object model,

00:10:32.560 --> 00:10:34.840
 how we can extend the document object model,

00:10:34.840 --> 00:10:37.640
 how we can fiddle with the CSS like show and hide,

00:10:37.640 --> 00:10:40.440
 and then how we can use fetch to make network requests

00:10:40.440 --> 00:10:43.800
 and we finished making web components.

00:10:43.800 --> 00:10:47.320
 So there's a lot to this and it gets really fun

00:10:47.320 --> 00:10:50.440
 when we start moving model data back and forth

00:10:50.440 --> 00:10:54.480
 between the server and the JavaScript.

00:10:54.480 --> 00:10:57.060
 (upbeat music)

